Lab 5 Higgs Classification

In tihs report, we will be working with an inclusive search for the standard model Higgs boson in pp collisions at s = 13 TeV at the LHC using simulated data. Our goal is to find the optimal event selections to enhance the discovery sensitivity by using our datasets, and the best event selections will be applied to a selected pseudo-experiment data.

What is Higgs Boson?

It is an rudimentary particle in the Standard Model of particle physics associated with the Higgs field, an energy field that transmits mass to the things that travel through it. It is produced with large transverse momentum (pT) and decaying to a bottom quark-antiquark pair. associated with the Higgs field, an energy field that transmits mass to the things that travel through it.

What is LHC?

The Large Hadron Collider (LHC) is the worlds largest and most powerful particle accelerator. It consists of a 27-kilometre ring of superconducting magnets with a number of accelerating structures to boost the energy of the particles along the way. Two high-energy particle beams travel inside the accelerator towards opposite directions at close to the speed of light before they are made to collide at four different points. The aim of the LHC's detectors is to allow physicists to test the predictions of different theories of particle physics, including measuring the properties of the Higgs boson and searching for the large family of new particles predicted by supersymmetric theories, as well as other unsolved questions of physics.

Features

There are fourteen features in our datasets:

  • 'pt' : The component of momentum in the transverse plane (X-Y plane) in the form of sqrt(p_x ^2 + p_y ^2).

  • 'eta' : The Pseudo rapidity in the form of , which is used to describe the angle of a particle relative to the beam axis.

  • 'phi' : The azimuthal angle which is an angular measurement in a spherical coordinate system.

  • 'mass' : The invariant mass is the portion of the total mass of an object or system of objects that is independent of the overall motion of the system. More precisely, it is a characteristic of the system's total energy and momentum that is the same in all frames of reference related by Lorentz transformations.

  • 'ee2' : The 2-point ECF ratio is the energy correlation function ratio for two-point correlators, and it is useful in quark/gluon discrimination.

  • 'ee3' : The 3-point ECF ratio is the energy correlation function ratio for three-point correlators, and it is useful in boosted W/Z/Higgs boson identification.

  • 'd2' : The 3-to-2 point ECF ratio.

  • 'angularity' : The symbol that describes the specific orientation of one feature to another at a referenced angle.

  • 't1' : The 1-subjettiness is a N-subjettiness with N = 1 that is a new jet shape designed to identify boosted hadronically-decaying objects like electroweak bosons and top quarks. N-subjettiness sums the angular distances of N jet constituents to their nearest subjet axis.

  • 't2' : The 2-subjettiness.

  • 't3' : The 3-subjettiness.

  • 't21' : The 21-subjettiness, which is the ratio between t2 and t1.

  • 't32' : The 32-subjettiness, which is the ratio between t3 and t2.

  • 'KtDeltaR' : The delta R of two subjets within the large-R jet.

Exploring the Datasets

We have two datasets, one is the signal dataset and another is the background data set. They both contains all 14 features explained above. We will first discover the data distribution of these two datasets by generating distribution plots in order to see whether all different features have discrimination power between signal and background, and then, we will be looking at their relationships with each other.

In [3]:
import pickle
%matplotlib inline
import numpy as np
import matplotlib
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.patches as mpatches
from scipy import stats

# open the file of interest, and use pickle loading
infile = open ("higgs_100000_pt_1000_1200.pkl",'rb')
higgs = pickle.load(infile)

infile2 = open ("qcd_100000_pt_1000_1200.pkl",'rb')
qcd = pickle.load(infile2)

plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (12, 8)

plt.hist(higgs['pt'][:], 100, color = 'maroon', density=True, alpha=0.3) 
plt.hist(qcd['pt'][:], 100, color = 'c', density=True, alpha=0.3)
plt.xlabel('Transverse Momentum (GeV)', fontsize=16) 
plt.ylabel('Probability', fontsize=16) 
plt.title('Signal & Background Transverse Momentum Distribution', fontsize=16)
maroon_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='maroon', label='Signal')
c_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='c', label='Background')
plt.legend(handles=[maroon_patch, c_patch])
Out[3]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fe9e75d56d0>

The above graph is the distribution of Transverse Momentum (pT) of both signal data and background data. The signal data are having a much greater probability in the range from 1080 GeV to 1120 GeV than out of this range. In contrast, the background data distribution showed an increasing probability around 1050 GeV. Also, compared with the right-skewed background distribution, the signal data are more skewed to the left. The difference between the distributions of background and signal data proves to have discrimination power.

Correlations

We have discovered the discrimination power of all features and proved that it is not every feature that provides an ability to clearly distinguish between signal and background data. Now, we will be moving onto discovery of the correlation between different features, and we are doing this by plotting out the scatter plot with different features.

  1. Transverse Momentum
In [36]:
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (15, 4)
fx, ax1 = plt.subplots(1, 1)
x = higgs['pt']
y = higgs['ee2']
ax1.scatter(x, y)
m1, b1 = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
ax1.plot(x, m1*x + b1, color = 'r', linewidth = 4)
ax1.set_xlabel('Transverse momentum')
ax1.set_ylabel('2-point ECF ratio')
ax1.set_title('Correlation between Transverse momentum and 2-point ECF ratio')
print(stats.pearsonr(x, y))

(-0.18470539032085964, 0.0)

From the above three graph, we can see that both the signal and background for the Transverse momentum feature has correlations with other features. The signal of Transverse momentum has a negative correlation with the 2-point ECF ratio with a correlation coefficient of -0.185, and it also has a negative correlation with the 3-point ECF ratio with -0.278 as its coefficient. The background of the Transverse momentum has a positive correlation with the mass with 0.1 as coefficient.

The above graghs plotted the correlations of signal of 2-point ECF ratio, we found three negative correlations with Transverse momentum, 3-to-2-point ECF ratio, angularity, and one positive correlation with mass.

Therefore, we can conclude that there exist correlations between different features in our datasets.

Conclusion

In the report, we have discovered the data and found out that some features have ambiguous discrimination power such as azimuthal angle, 2-point ECF ratio, 3-point ECF ratio, 3-to-2-point ECF ratio, and 32-subjettiness, where some have certain power to be distinguished from other features. Furthermore, there contains high correlations between different features. Therefore, in order to get a optimal discovery sensitivity, it is necessary and helpful to drop those features' data where the discrimination power is low and correlation is strong.
